04123nam a22006495i 9780748631049DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20222007stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486310497 a10.1515/97807486310492doi  a(DE-B1597)615807  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0000002bisacsh1 aOlkowski, Dorothea, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Universal (In the Realm of the Sensible) :bBeyond Continental Philosophy /cDorothea Olkowski. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPlateaus - New Directions in Deleuze Studies : PLAT00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- t1. Philosophy and the Limits of Difference -- t2. ‘A Place of Love and Mystery’ -- t3. ‘Love and Hatred’ -- t4. ‘Under Western Eyes’ -- t5. Passive Restraint -- t6. In the Realm of the Sensible -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Universal (In the realm of the sensible): Beyond Continental Philosophy proposes a radical, new philosophical system that moves from ontology to ethics. Dorothea Olkowski develops the concept of an ontological unconscious, a connection arising from our sensible relation to the world that conditions encounters with the environment and with others. This fundamental ontology rethinks the space-time relations opened by Irigaray’s notion of the ‘interval,’ Bergson’s ‘recollection,’ Merleau-Ponty’s idea of the ‘flesh’ and Deleuze’s ‘plane of immanence’. Writing in an original style, inspired by literature and the arts, Olkowski locates a ‘realm of the senses’, a field of vulnerability, felt as pleasures and pains. This presents an aesthetic sense of something universal to all human kind, as well as to the organic and inorganic world.In addition to this proposal for a wider ontology, the relation between traditional ontologies and politics is examined as a means of opening politics beyond a no exit or limit cycle. Instead a multiplicity of self-organized, emergent perspectives emerges, eliminating the need for the connections, conjunctions, and disjunctions of the Kantian paradigm at work in contemporary continental philosophy.This is a timely, controversial and important book that contributes enormously to the study of Deleuze and Continental Philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aContinental philosophy. 0aOntology. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748631049zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748631049423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748631049/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK